/*--------------------------------*- Choupo -*-----------------------*\
  GLOBAL thermo foundation -- cascades DOWN to both sectors (REACTION, SEPARATION).

  idealGas for BOTH sectors (γ-φ with φ = 1).  Decided from evidence:
  - REACTION runs at 900 K / 35 bar, all-vapour -- ideal gas is genuinely
    accurate there, and the conversionReactor's duty comes from h_ig on the
    elements datum (standardThermochemistry), which is exact.
  - SEPARATION's flash split is K = Psat/P.  At 320 K this is a wide, robust
    spread (H2 K~50, CH4 K~11, benzene K~0.009, toluene K~0.003) that cleanly
    sends H2/CH4 to the gas and the aromatics to the liquid.  SRK/PR add no
    rigour here (they correct only the vapour φ; the liquid still uses the same
    Antoine extrapolation for the supercritical gases) so they would change the
    answer without making it honest.

  HONEST CAVEAT (state it in the case header): the gas-phase K-values for the
  light, supercritical species (H2, CH4) rest on Antoine EXTRAPOLATION out of
  range.  The split is physically sensible and the mole balances are exact, but
  the gas-phase compositions are first-order, not design-grade.  The
  benzene/toluene column, by contrast, is both subcritical and in-range -- there
  idealGas is genuinely accurate.
\*---------------------------------------------------------------------------*/

components       ( toluene  H2  benzene  CH4 );

activityModel    { model  ideal; }
equationOfState  { model  idealGas; }
